<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="301" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[136,774,509,629]" pageId="1" pageNumber="301">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,246,509,533]" pageId="1" pageNumber="301">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Wood-Mason, in Wood-Mason &amp; Alcock, 1891" authorityName="Wood-Mason, in Wood-Mason &amp; Alcock" authorityYear="1891" class="Malacostraca" family="Leucosiidae" genus="Parilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[251,326,509,533]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="301">Parilia</emphasis>
Wood-Mason, in 
<bibRefCitation author="Wood-Mason J &amp; Alcock A" pageId="1" pageNumber="301" pagination="258 - 272" refId="ref11528" refString="Wood-Mason J &amp; Alcock A (1891) Natural History Notes from H. M. Indian Marine Survey Steamer &quot; Investigator &quot;, Commander R. F. Hoskyn, R. N., commanding. No. 21. On the Results of the last Season's Deepsea Dredging. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, March 1891, (6) 7 (39): 258 - 272. [For an elaboration on the authorship of the taxa described in this series of papers, see HUYS et al., 2014.]" type="journal article" year="1891">Wood-Mason &amp; Alcock, 1891</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, is here restricted for three species, with 
<taxonomicName authority="Sakai, 1961" authorityName="Sakai" authorityYear="1961" class="Malacostraca" family="Leucosiidae" genus="Parilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculata">
<emphasis box="[622,774,541,565]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="301">P. tuberculata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Sakai T" box="[136,272,573,597]" pageId="1" pageNumber="301" pagination="131 - 150" refId="ref10919" refString="Sakai T (1961) New species of Japanese crabs from the collection of His Majesty the Emperor of Japan. Crustaceana, 3 (2): 131 - 150, figs. 1 - 4, pls. 3, 4." type="journal article" year="1961">Sakai, 1961</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, referred to its own genus (see remarks for next genus).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[136,775,669,1045]" pageId="1" pageNumber="301">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wood-Mason, in Wood-Mason &amp; Alcock" authorityYear="1891" box="[136,296,669,693]" class="Malacostraca" family="Leucosiidae" genus="Parilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alcocki">
<emphasis box="[136,296,669,693]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="301">Parilia alcocki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sakai" authorityYear="1961" box="[349,443,670,693]" class="Malacostraca" family="Leucosiidae" genus="Parilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="major">
<emphasis box="[349,443,670,693]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="301">P. major</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the two largest leucosioids known in the world, with adults exceeding 
<quantity box="[659,740,701,725]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="301" unit="mm" value="70.0">70 mm</quantity>
in carapace width. Alcock (1899: 29) recorded males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wood-Mason, in Wood-Mason &amp; Alcock" authorityYear="1891" class="Malacostraca" family="Leucosiidae" genus="Parilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alcocki">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="301">P. alcocki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<quantity box="[225,305,765,789]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.6" pageId="1" pageNumber="301" unit="mm" value="56.0">56 mm</quantity>
in carapace width with a largest male in the present study measuring 
<quantity box="[464,564,797,821]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.06" pageId="1" pageNumber="301" unit="mm" value="70.6">70.6 mm</quantity>
(CASAU). For 
<taxonomicName authority=", Chen &amp; Sun (2002: 366)" authorityName="Chen &amp; Sun" authorityPageNumber="366" authorityYear="2002" class="Malacostraca" family="Leucosiidae" genus="Parilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="major">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="301">P. major</emphasis>
, Chen &amp; Sun (2002: 366)
</taxonomicName>
recorded a large male 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.01" pageId="1" pageNumber="301" unit="mm" value="60.1">60.1 mm</quantity>
in carapace width while in the present material, there is a male measuring 70.0 mm (ZRC 2001.552). 
<taxonomicName authority="Stimpson, 1871" authorityName="Stimpson" authorityYear="1871" class="Malacostraca" family="Leucosiidae" genus="Myropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quinquespinosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="301">Myropsis quinquespinosa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Stimpson W" box="[312,484,925,949]" pageId="1" pageNumber="301" pagination="109 - 160" refId="ref11082" refString="Stimpson W (1871) Brachyura. In: Preliminary Report on the Crustacea dredged in the Gulf Stream in the Straits of Florida, by L. F. de Pourtales, Assist. U. S. Coast Survey. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard College, 2 (2): 109 - 160." type="journal article" year="1871">Stimpson, 1871</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, from the western Atlantic coast has been reported to grow to carapace widths of 65.0 mm and 68.0 mm by 
<bibRefCitation author="Rathbun MJ" box="[384,616,989,1013]" pageId="1" pageNumber="301" pagination="1 - 278" refId="ref10882" refString="Rathbun MJ (1937) The oxystomatous and allied crabs of America. Bulletin of the U. S. National Museum, 166: i-vi, 1 - 278, pls. 1 - 86." type="journal article" year="1937">Rathbun (1937: 166)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Williams AB" pageId="1" pageNumber="301" refId="ref11396" refString="Williams AB (1984) Shrimps, Lobsters, and Crabs of the Atlantic Coast of the Eastern United States, Maine to Florida. Smithsonian Institution Press, 550 pp." type="book" year="1984">Williams (1984: 287)</bibRefCitation>
, respectively.
</paragraph>
